him which immediatly before, charged the author of the Apologie, to vse an argument more like a tinker, than a diuine? you shall heare his argument of authority of Chrysostom, Hom. de Eucharistia. Diddest thou not promise the Preist, when he cried, Lift vp your minds and hearts: and saiedst thou not: we lift them vp vnto our Lord? Will you see a wonderfull matter? The table is furnished with the mysteries. The lambe of God is offered for thee, the Priest is hofull for thee, a spirituall fire floweth from the table. Loe here be the mysteries vppon the table, heere is the lambe of God offered which is the sacrifice of the Masse. But I pray you sir, what is the spirituall fire that floweth from the table? O that is a figuratiue speech, you will say, alluding to the burned offering of the old law. Nay, if ye haue figures of rhetorike, then you haue no trueth, you haue but foolish dreames, you haue nothing made by your wordes. Is not this your owne Logike, Master Sander?
               
               
