nioy those things, which God giueth, and to lead his life peaceably &amp; iustly. Eccle. 3. v. 12. Finally where Sander concludeth, that the custom of ye scripture, in commending so much bread and wine, sheweth yt the body &amp; bloud of Christ should

be giuen vnder their forms: I say it may more probably be gathered to shew, yt bread &amp; wine are appointed to be the seals of our spiritual feeding, wt the body &amp; bloud of Christ. For it is a strange maner of cōmending, to praise the substance for ye only bare shewes &amp; accidents therof. Although the scripture in most of these places cited, intendeth in deede, neither the one conclusiō, nor ye other▪
                  
               
               
